1
00:01:11,863 --> 00:01:16,414
<i>JOR-EL:
You will travel far, my little Kal-El.</i>

2
00:01:16,994 --> 00:01:19,167
<i>But we will never leave you...</i>

3
00:01:19,580 --> 00:01:22,254
<i>even in the face of our deaths.</i>

4
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:26,049
<i>You will make my strength your own.</i>

5
00:01:27,379 --> 00:01:30,679
<i>You will see my life through your eyes...</i>

6
00:01:31,633 --> 00:01:34,386
<i>as your life will be seen through mine.</i>

7
00:01:35,721 --> 00:01:41,899
<i>The son becomes the father,
and the father the son.</i>

8
00:05:07,474 --> 00:05:10,023
<i>GERTRUDE:
In spite of your past...</i>

9
00:05:10,227 --> 00:05:11,945
[THUNDER CRASHES]

10
00:05:12,270 --> 00:05:14,989
L know you're a good man.

11
00:05:16,483 --> 00:05:18,281
And all good men...

12
00:05:18,819 --> 00:05:21,322
deserve a second chance.

13
00:05:22,531 --> 00:05:24,329
[COUGHING]

14
00:05:29,371 --> 00:05:32,466
From the moment
I received your first letter...

15
00:05:32,624 --> 00:05:35,468
I knew you were not like the rest.

16
00:05:37,003 --> 00:05:40,928
You came from nothing...

17
00:05:41,550 --> 00:05:44,394
and you worked so hard
to get where you are.

18
00:05:45,345 --> 00:05:48,189
You might have made a few mistakes.

19
00:05:48,557 --> 00:05:51,437
MAN 1: Gertrude, for God's sake!
MAN 2: Damn it, Gertrude, let us in now!

20
00:05:51,726 --> 00:05:57,153
You said that if I helped you
get out of prison...

21
00:05:58,275 --> 00:06:00,824
you'd take care of me.
MAN: Mm-hm.

22
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:03,993
And you have.

23
00:06:05,365 --> 00:06:08,710
You've shown me pleasures
that I've never known.

24
00:06:08,869 --> 00:06:10,462
MAN: Mm.

25
00:06:11,288 --> 00:06:13,507
That's why you deserve...

26
00:06:13,665 --> 00:06:15,588
everything.

27
00:06:19,045 --> 00:06:20,547
I love you...

28
00:06:21,089 --> 00:06:23,137
Lex Luthor.

29
00:06:24,092 --> 00:06:25,309
[GERTRUDE GROANS]

30
00:06:39,357 --> 00:06:41,860
MAN 1:
Gertrude, let us in. He's a crook.

31
00:06:42,027 --> 00:06:44,075
MAN 2:
He doesn't love you, Gertrude!

32
00:06:44,237 --> 00:06:45,614
WOMAN: He's a monster! Gertrude!

33
00:07:03,256 --> 00:07:05,475
- You can keep that.
WOMAN: Oh, God.

34
00:07:05,634 --> 00:07:06,931
The rest is mine.

35
00:07:07,135 --> 00:07:09,513
[SHRIEKS]

36
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:15,068
We're done.

37
00:07:36,581 --> 00:07:38,754
[ENGINE REVVING]

38
00:07:44,589 --> 00:07:46,762
MAN: Bye, Martha.

39
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:49,933
[MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO]

40
00:08:13,576 --> 00:08:15,544
[STATIC ON RADIO]

41
00:08:16,997 --> 00:08:18,795
[MUSIC STOPS]

42
00:08:23,962 --> 00:08:25,714
[LOW RUMBLING]

43
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:51,952
[ROARING OVERHEAD]

44
00:09:08,298 --> 00:09:10,972
[MUSIC PLAYS]

45
00:10:04,270 --> 00:10:07,399
[LOW HUMMING]

46
00:10:21,871 --> 00:10:23,418
Oh! Oh.

47
00:10:23,581 --> 00:10:25,675
Oh, Clark.

48
00:10:28,586 --> 00:10:31,430
Oh, my boy.

49
00:10:46,604 --> 00:10:48,698
[THUNDER CRASHING]

50
00:11:19,470 --> 00:11:22,144
Will you get that thing out of my face!

51
00:11:25,476 --> 00:11:27,319
[OPERA MUSIC PLAYS ON STEREO]

52
00:11:28,730 --> 00:11:30,824
KITTY:
Lex, your friends give me the creeps.

53
00:11:30,982 --> 00:11:32,859
LEX:
Prison is a creepy place, Kitty.

54
00:11:33,026 --> 00:11:35,495
One needs to make creepy friends
in order to survive.

55
00:11:35,653 --> 00:11:38,156
Even a man with my vast talents
is worth less inside...

56
00:11:38,323 --> 00:11:42,203
than a carton of cigarettes and
a sharp piece of metal in your pocket.

57
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:44,287
[LEX SIGHS]

58
00:11:45,872 --> 00:11:49,046
Do you know the story of Prometheus?
No, of course you don't.

59
00:11:49,209 --> 00:11:53,259
Prometheus was a god who stole
the power of fire from the other gods...

60
00:11:53,421 --> 00:11:55,173
and gave control of it to mortals.

61
00:11:55,340 --> 00:11:58,014
In essence, he gave us technology.
He gave us power.

62
00:11:58,176 --> 00:12:01,726
So we're stealing fire? In the Arctic.

63
00:12:01,888 --> 00:12:05,518
Actually, sort of. You see, whoever
controls technology controls the world.

64
00:12:05,683 --> 00:12:08,357
The Roman Empire ruled the world
because they built roads.

65
00:12:08,519 --> 00:12:11,489
The British Empire ruled the world
because they built ships.

66
00:12:11,648 --> 00:12:15,198
America, the atom bomb,
and so on and so forth.

67
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:17,033
I just want what Prometheus wanted.

68
00:12:17,362 --> 00:12:21,037
Sounds great, Lex, but you're not a god.

69
00:12:24,035 --> 00:12:27,084
Gods are selfish beings
who fly around in little red capes...

70
00:12:27,247 --> 00:12:29,545
and don't share their power
with mankind.

71
00:12:29,707 --> 00:12:31,334
THUG: Hey, boss.

72
00:12:31,960 --> 00:12:33,587
We found something.

73
00:12:38,508 --> 00:12:41,227
LEX: No, I don't wanna be a god.

74
00:12:41,386 --> 00:12:44,481
I just wanna bring fire to the people.

75
00:12:45,556 --> 00:12:49,231
And I want my cut.

76
00:13:29,559 --> 00:13:31,232
KITTY: Wow.

77
00:13:31,936 --> 00:13:34,280
THUG: Was this his house?

78
00:13:35,064 --> 00:13:37,658
LEX:
You might think so. Most would.

79
00:13:37,817 --> 00:13:40,866
This is more of a monument
to a long dead...

80
00:13:41,029 --> 00:13:43,623
and extremely powerful civilization.

81
00:13:43,781 --> 00:13:46,455
This is where he learned who he was.

82
00:13:46,951 --> 00:13:49,625
This is where he came for guidance.

83
00:14:00,548 --> 00:14:02,642
Possibilities.

84
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:06,850
Endless possibilities.

85
00:14:51,808 --> 00:14:54,812
You act like you've been here before.

86
00:15:20,878 --> 00:15:22,721
JOR-EL [ON RECORDING]: My <i>son...</i>

87
00:15:25,216 --> 00:15:27,639
<i>you do not remember me.</i>

88
00:15:28,594 --> 00:15:30,722
<i>I am Jor-El.</i>

89
00:15:31,139 --> 00:15:33,233
<i>I'm your father.</i>

90
00:15:33,391 --> 00:15:37,487
<i>By now, I will have been dead
many thousands of your years.</i>

91
00:15:37,645 --> 00:15:41,149
<i>- He thinks I'm his son.
- You are the only survivor of Krypton.</i>

92
00:15:41,774 --> 00:15:46,996
<i>Embedded in the crystals before you is
the total accumulation of all literature...</i>

93
00:15:47,155 --> 00:15:50,034
and <i>scientific fact
from dozens of other worlds...</i>

94
00:15:50,199 --> 00:15:53,624
<i>spanning the 28 known galaxies.</i>

95
00:15:54,120 --> 00:15:56,589
<i>There are questions to be asked.</i>

96
00:15:57,206 --> 00:15:58,879
<i>Here in this...</i>

97
00:15:59,041 --> 00:16:01,544
<i>This Fortress of Solitude...</i>

98
00:16:02,086 --> 00:16:05,590
<i>we shall try to find
the answers together.</i>

99
00:16:05,756 --> 00:16:07,258
KITTY: Can he see us?

100
00:16:08,009 --> 00:16:09,636
No, he's dead.

101
00:16:10,845 --> 00:16:12,188
<i>So, my son...</i>

102
00:16:15,766 --> 00:16:17,609
<i>Kal-El...</i>

103
00:16:21,105 --> 00:16:23,153
<i>speak.</i>

104
00:16:24,817 --> 00:16:26,785
Tell me everything...

105
00:16:26,944 --> 00:16:29,572
starting with crystals.

106
00:16:56,516 --> 00:16:58,189
[ROOSTER CROWING]

107
00:18:40,703 --> 00:18:42,671
[GRUNTS]

108
00:19:21,702 --> 00:19:22,794
[DOG WHINES]

109
00:19:26,415 --> 00:19:27,883
<i>Hey, DOV-</i>

110
00:19:45,476 --> 00:19:46,728
[WHINES]

111
00:19:53,984 --> 00:19:55,986
WOMAN 1 [ON TV]:
<i>On Tuesday, between support...</i>

112
00:19:56,153 --> 00:19:58,497
MAN 1: <i>Hindered the firefighting efforts
for all those...</i>

113
00:19:58,656 --> 00:20:03,332
MAN <i>2: Police have finally arrived and
it's still complete mayhem down here.</i>

114
00:20:03,494 --> 00:20:07,089
MAN 3: <i>Fighting broke out in the
southernmost region...</i>

115
00:20:07,248 --> 00:20:09,671
<i>with border fire
and small-arms attacks prevalent.</i>

116
00:20:09,834 --> 00:20:11,586
Don't worry, I buried it this morning.

117
00:20:11,752 --> 00:20:14,847
WOMAN 2: <i>It was futile trying to force
him to testify beforeagrand jury.</i>

118
00:20:15,005 --> 00:20:16,507
Mom?

119
00:20:17,925 --> 00:20:19,927
Five years.

120
00:20:21,846 --> 00:20:25,225
If your father was alive,
he never would have let you go.

121
00:20:25,933 --> 00:20:27,526
I almost gave up hope.

122
00:20:27,685 --> 00:20:30,939
I just thought
I would never see you again.

123
00:20:31,689 --> 00:20:34,283
Oh, Clark.

124
00:20:41,532 --> 00:20:44,206
Did you find what you were looking for?

125
00:20:45,035 --> 00:20:48,756
I thought, hoped...

126
00:20:49,582 --> 00:20:51,380
it might still be there.

127
00:20:52,084 --> 00:20:53,882
Your home?

128
00:20:56,380 --> 00:20:58,724
That place was a graveyard.

129
00:21:00,217 --> 00:21:01,639
I'm all that's left.

130
00:21:03,888 --> 00:21:07,438
Clark, the universe is a big place.

131
00:21:07,975 --> 00:21:10,228
And you don't know who's out there.

132
00:21:12,021 --> 00:21:14,490
And even if you are the last...

133
00:21:17,067 --> 00:21:18,910
you're not alone.

134
00:21:23,741 --> 00:21:25,334
I know.

135
00:21:35,085 --> 00:21:36,211
[ELEVATOR DINGS]

136
00:21:36,420 --> 00:21:38,218
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

137
00:21:46,931 --> 00:21:48,131
CLARK: Sorry. MAN 1: Look out!

138
00:21:48,265 --> 00:21:49,517
MAN 2: Watch out, will you?

139
00:21:49,683 --> 00:21:51,185
- WOMAN: Excuse me.
- Sorry.

140
00:21:52,770 --> 00:21:54,113
Sorry.

141
00:21:55,606 --> 00:21:58,610
Great. Would you be careful?

142
00:21:59,610 --> 00:22:03,114
- Jimmy.
- Mr. Clark! I mean, Kent! Mr. Kent!

143
00:22:03,280 --> 00:22:04,907
Welcome back! Oh, my God!

144
00:22:05,074 --> 00:22:09,295
Um, hey, come... Uh, wait right there.
I'll be right back.

145
00:22:18,754 --> 00:22:22,224
Oh, hey, sorry, guys,
I'm still looking for a place to live...

146
00:22:22,383 --> 00:22:24,135
if you know of anything reasonable.

147
00:22:24,301 --> 00:22:25,644
Behind you, Mr. Kent.

148
00:22:25,803 --> 00:22:27,055
[JIMMY LAUGHS]

149
00:22:27,221 --> 00:22:29,644
I made it myself. It's a cake.

150
00:22:29,849 --> 00:22:31,351
Oh, it looks...

151
00:22:32,393 --> 00:22:33,645
delicious.

152
00:22:33,811 --> 00:22:38,157
Olsen! Where are the photos
of that birthday-clown-massacre thing?

153
00:22:38,315 --> 00:22:40,864
I'm on it, chief. Hey, look who's back.

154
00:22:41,277 --> 00:22:42,654
Kent? CLARK: Hey, chief.

155
00:22:42,820 --> 00:22:45,020
- Thank you for giving me my job back.
- Don't thank me.

156
00:22:45,155 --> 00:22:46,828
Thank Norm Palmer for dying.

157
00:22:48,701 --> 00:22:50,669
It was his time.

158
00:22:51,954 --> 00:22:55,128
- Let's get you set up, huh?
PERRY: Olsen!

159
00:22:55,291 --> 00:22:57,009
Uh, okay, so I gotta run...

160
00:22:57,167 --> 00:23:00,421
but I will be back to check on you
in a sec, Mr. Kent.

161
00:23:00,588 --> 00:23:04,764
Oh, hey, do you know
where I can find Lois?

162
00:23:18,689 --> 00:23:21,067
<i>The timing of this
automated-ignition countdown...</i>

163
00:23:21,233 --> 00:23:23,361
<i>is the most precarious part
of the launch.</i>

164
00:23:23,694 --> 00:23:25,196
LOIS [ON TV]:
Lois Lane, Daily Planet.

165
00:23:25,362 --> 00:23:28,616
<i>You also stated that the shuttle
will usher in a new era of travel...</i>

166
00:23:28,782 --> 00:23:31,831
<i>enabling the average person
to afford transcontinental flights.</i>

167
00:23:31,994 --> 00:23:34,088
<i>But can you tell us the exact price...</i>

168
00:23:34,246 --> 00:23:36,840
<i>an "average person"
will be expected to pay?</i>

169
00:23:37,041 --> 00:23:39,715
WOMAN: <i>The answer to that question
is in your press packet.</i>

170
00:23:39,877 --> 00:23:42,630
<i>The Earth is surrounded
byablanket of air...</i>

171
00:23:42,796 --> 00:23:45,174
<i>which we call the atmosphere.</i>

172
00:24:33,847 --> 00:24:37,772
Huh! Yeah. He looks just like his mom.

173
00:24:37,935 --> 00:24:41,940
Already takes after her too, especially
when it comes to getting into trouble.

174
00:24:42,106 --> 00:24:43,608
Mother?

175
00:24:45,442 --> 00:24:50,118
Oh, yeah, well, I guess you've been gone.
Fearless reporter Lois Lane is a mommy.

176
00:24:50,322 --> 00:24:51,995
[c RACKS]

177
00:24:52,449 --> 00:24:55,749
Oh, you know, um, I'll just...
I'll take that. That's good.

178
00:24:55,911 --> 00:24:58,835
- Sorry.
- No. Um, she's got plenty.

179
00:24:58,998 --> 00:25:00,966
- Wait, she's married?
- Yes.

180
00:25:01,458 --> 00:25:05,508
No. Not really. It's more like
a prolonged engagement.

181
00:25:05,671 --> 00:25:08,140
But don't ask Miss Lane
when they're tying the knot...

182
00:25:08,298 --> 00:25:11,848
because she hates that question.

183
00:25:12,011 --> 00:25:16,482
<i>Like this follow the same stringent
safety guidelines set by NASA?</i>

184
00:25:16,640 --> 00:25:19,268
<i>Since this is a joint venture
with the Air Force...</i>

185
00:25:19,643 --> 00:25:22,988
You all right? You look like
you could use a drink.

186
00:25:25,357 --> 00:25:28,611
KITTY: This place is so tacky.
Why are we back here?

187
00:25:28,777 --> 00:25:32,407
LEX: While you were doing your nails
and ordering fur coats online...

188
00:25:32,573 --> 00:25:34,325
I was busy unlocking the secrets...

189
00:25:34,491 --> 00:25:37,370
of one of the most advanced
civilizations in the universe.

190
00:25:37,536 --> 00:25:38,788
Weren't there two of those?

191
00:25:38,954 --> 00:25:43,209
LEX: You see, unlike our clunky
earthbound forms of construction...

192
00:25:43,375 --> 00:25:45,844
the technology on Krypton,
Superman's home world...

193
00:25:46,003 --> 00:25:48,222
was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.

194
00:25:48,380 --> 00:25:49,973
KITTY:
Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.

195
00:25:50,132 --> 00:25:53,887
LEX: Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...

196
00:25:54,053 --> 00:25:56,181
would be indistinguishable from magic.

197
00:25:56,346 --> 00:26:00,726
But imagine: Cities, vehicles, weapons...

198
00:26:01,310 --> 00:26:02,937
entire continents...

199
00:26:03,145 --> 00:26:04,237
[ELECTRICITY HUMS]

200
00:26:04,396 --> 00:26:06,023
All grown.

201
00:26:13,697 --> 00:26:17,042
To think that one could create
a new world...

202
00:26:17,201 --> 00:26:20,205
with such a simple little object.

203
00:26:21,121 --> 00:26:22,168
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

204
00:26:22,331 --> 00:26:24,208
It's like a seed.

205
00:26:24,374 --> 00:26:26,627
And all it needs is water.

206
00:26:26,794 --> 00:26:28,262
Like...

207
00:26:29,046 --> 00:26:31,048
Sea-Monkeys.

208
00:26:32,716 --> 00:26:35,014
Exactly, Kitty.

209
00:26:35,552 --> 00:26:37,225
Like Sea-Monkeys.

210
00:26:39,431 --> 00:26:44,028
Clark has been doing a little
soul-searching for the last couple years.

211
00:26:44,186 --> 00:26:46,188
- He saw llamas.
BARTENDER: Yeah?

212
00:26:46,355 --> 00:26:48,403
- Yeah.
- Must be tough coming back.

213
00:26:50,109 --> 00:26:52,282
- Coming back?
- To work.

214
00:26:53,195 --> 00:26:54,663
Yeah.

215
00:26:55,072 --> 00:26:57,666
Well, you know, things change.

216
00:26:57,825 --> 00:26:59,873
I mean, of course things change...

217
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:05,917
but sometimes things that you didn't
think would change could change.

218
00:27:06,375 --> 00:27:07,968
Take Lois.

219
00:27:08,127 --> 00:27:12,098
A woman like her,
I never thought she'd settle down.

220
00:27:12,548 --> 00:27:16,223
You know, if you ask me...
Because she'll never tell you this...

221
00:27:16,385 --> 00:27:21,266
but if you ask me,
she's still in love with you-know-who.

222
00:27:29,606 --> 00:27:33,486
WOMAN: The original space shuttle
generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust...

223
00:27:33,652 --> 00:27:35,370
just in the initial launch phase.

224
00:27:35,529 --> 00:27:40,285
But, by piggybacking
on this Boeing 777... Yes?

225
00:27:40,450 --> 00:27:42,498
If this launch is as
pivotal as you claim...

226
00:27:42,661 --> 00:27:44,959
why is it being covered
by one news network?

227
00:27:45,122 --> 00:27:48,342
Why don't we save those questions
for the post-launch briefing.

228
00:27:48,500 --> 00:27:50,127
How about that, Miss Lane?

229
00:27:50,294 --> 00:27:53,764
When we hit 40,000 feet,
the shuttle will detach, ascend...

230
00:27:53,922 --> 00:27:57,643
and then fire the first of two propellant
systems, the liquid fuel boosters.

231
00:27:57,801 --> 00:27:59,849
When the shuttle
reaches the stratosphere...

232
00:28:00,012 --> 00:28:02,140
the secondary
insertion booster will fire...

233
00:28:02,306 --> 00:28:05,685
propelling the craft
at 4gs into the mesosphere.

234
00:28:09,521 --> 00:28:11,694
- Careful.
- I know.

235
00:28:12,524 --> 00:28:15,528
- Careful. Careful.
- I know.

236
00:28:29,166 --> 00:28:30,918
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

237
00:28:42,763 --> 00:28:45,232
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

238
00:28:45,390 --> 00:28:47,688
Wait for it.

239
00:28:51,104 --> 00:28:53,857
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

240
00:28:56,318 --> 00:28:59,037
<i>It's freaking Gone With the Wind.</i>

241
00:28:59,696 --> 00:29:01,744
- Shut off the camera.
- But I'm getting it.

242
00:29:01,907 --> 00:29:03,955
I said, shut off the damn camera.

243
00:29:10,332 --> 00:29:12,050
THUG:
I think I did something wrong.

244
00:29:12,209 --> 00:29:16,555
