00:48:44,713 --> 00:48:47,557
It was hard to say goodbye
because he had to go...

478
00:48:47,716 --> 00:48:51,095
and he wanted to say goodbye,
but maybe it was too difficult for him.

479
00:48:51,262 --> 00:48:54,641
Difficult? What's so difficult about it?
"Goodbye." It's easy.

480
00:48:54,807 --> 00:48:57,481
- What's so hard about saying goodbye?
- Uh...

481
00:48:57,643 --> 00:48:59,236
Who are we talking about?

482
00:48:59,395 --> 00:49:02,239
Nobody, just forget I said anything.

483
00:49:02,398 --> 00:49:04,400
Taxi! Hey!

484
00:49:05,234 --> 00:49:06,861
Taxi!

485
00:49:07,027 --> 00:49:08,449
[WHISTLES LOUDLY]

486
00:49:08,654 --> 00:49:10,531
[TIRES SCREECH]

487
00:49:11,657 --> 00:49:13,409
Wow, thanks.

488
00:49:16,620 --> 00:49:18,463
312 Riverside Drive, please.

489
00:49:19,331 --> 00:49:21,129
Good night, Clark.

490
00:49:34,221 --> 00:49:36,019
BOY: Superman!

491
00:50:48,587 --> 00:50:50,385
[PLAYING "CHOPSTICKS"
ON KEYBOARD]

492
00:50:50,923 --> 00:50:52,175
<i>I want egg rolls.</i>

493
00:50:52,341 --> 00:50:53,388
<i>LOIS: Nice try, kiddo.</i>

494
00:50:53,551 --> 00:50:56,521
<i>Only steamed chicken
and snow peas for you.</i>

495
00:50:57,846 --> 00:50:59,848
<i>RICHARD:
Why do we order Chinese if he's allergic?</i>

496
00:51:00,015 --> 00:51:01,733
<i>LOIS:
Because he loves the peas...</i>

497
00:51:01,892 --> 00:51:04,520
and I think we all prefer egg rolls
over macrobiotic shakes.

498
00:51:04,687 --> 00:51:05,904
Blech.

499
00:51:06,063 --> 00:51:07,986
- It's a good point.
- Mm.

500
00:51:20,995 --> 00:51:24,044
So I noticed you've been acting
a little different lately.

501
00:51:24,206 --> 00:51:25,833
Havel?

502
00:51:28,210 --> 00:51:32,340
You know, Lois,
that article that you wrote.

503
00:51:32,506 --> 00:51:34,429
"Why the World
Doesn't Need Superman"?

504
00:51:34,592 --> 00:51:38,472
No, no, no. No, the other one,
from years ago, before we met.

505
00:51:38,637 --> 00:51:42,187
Which article? I wrote dozens about him.
I was practically his press agent.

506
00:51:42,349 --> 00:51:44,272
"L Spent the Night With Superman."

507
00:51:48,564 --> 00:51:50,362
Richard, come on.

508
00:51:50,524 --> 00:51:52,492
It was the title of an interview.

509
00:51:52,818 --> 00:51:54,661
Plus, it was your Uncle Perry's idea.

510
00:51:54,820 --> 00:51:57,869
- No, I know, I know. It's okay, it's okay.
- Richard.

511
00:51:58,449 --> 00:52:00,497
It was a long time ago.

512
00:52:02,578 --> 00:52:04,080
Were you in love with him?

513
00:52:06,332 --> 00:52:10,087
He was Superman.
Everyone was in love with him.

514
00:52:11,378 --> 00:52:12,595
But were you?

515
00:52:21,513 --> 00:52:22,935
<i>No.</i>

516
00:52:23,098 --> 00:52:25,271
<i>RICHARD:
Lois, I shouldn't have brought it up.</i>

517
00:52:45,954 --> 00:52:48,457
JOR-EL: <i>Even though you've been
raised asahuman being...</i>

518
00:52:48,624 --> 00:52:50,718
<i>you are not one of them.</i>

519
00:52:54,880 --> 00:52:58,134
<i>They can be a great people, Kai-El.
They wish to be.</i>

520
00:52:59,176 --> 00:53:02,476
<i>They only lack the light
to show the way.</i>

521
00:53:02,888 --> 00:53:06,643
<i>For this reason above all,
their capacity for good...</i>

522
00:53:06,809 --> 00:53:08,811
<i>I have sent them you...</i>

523
00:53:08,977 --> 00:53:10,945
<i>my only son.</i>

524
00:53:23,409 --> 00:53:26,538
[DISTANT NOISES AND CHATTERING]

525
00:53:39,883 --> 00:53:42,807
[ALARM RINGS]

526
00:53:47,641 --> 00:53:49,018
[BOOMS]

527
00:53:50,519 --> 00:53:51,862
[SIRENS WAILING]

528
00:54:25,387 --> 00:54:26,559
Load them up.

529
00:54:54,249 --> 00:54:55,296
Holy sh...

530
00:55:12,309 --> 00:55:14,482
[MUFFLED GUNFIRE]

531
00:55:31,245 --> 00:55:32,963
[GRUNTING]

532
00:56:48,196 --> 00:56:49,368
WOMAN [OVER PA]: Attention...

533
00:56:49,531 --> 00:56:51,659
<i>the Metropolis Museum
of Natural History...</i>

534
00:56:51,825 --> 00:56:54,544
<i>will be closing in 10 minutes.
We hope that you've...</i>

535
00:56:54,703 --> 00:56:56,580
Sir, we're closing in 10 minutes.

536
00:56:56,747 --> 00:56:58,465
[IN SOUTHERN ACCENT]
We only need five.

537
00:57:08,717 --> 00:57:09,843
[SHRIEKING]

538
00:57:10,093 --> 00:57:11,891
[HONKING]

539
00:57:34,284 --> 00:57:36,378
[CHATTERING]

540
00:57:45,629 --> 00:57:48,633
You're done, the museum's closed.
Thank you.

541
00:59:06,460 --> 00:59:08,462
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

542
00:59:09,755 --> 00:59:11,007
Are you all right, miss?

543
00:59:11,173 --> 00:59:13,847
- My heart. I... I...
- I'm sorry?

544
00:59:14,217 --> 00:59:19,314
I have a palpitation,
a heart palpitation. And a murmur.

545
00:59:19,473 --> 00:59:20,645
- Please...
- Oh.

546
00:59:20,807 --> 00:59:22,184
Take me to the hospital.

547
00:59:22,350 --> 00:59:23,693
[SOBBING]

548
00:59:23,852 --> 00:59:26,071
Take me to the hospital.

549
00:59:36,073 --> 00:59:38,701
Just hold on tight.

550
01:00:15,862 --> 01:00:17,455
Bingo.

551
01:00:45,058 --> 01:00:46,526
- There you are, ma'am.
- My heart.

552
01:00:47,394 --> 01:00:50,568
My palpitations, they're gone.
What did you do?

553
01:00:50,730 --> 01:00:52,323
I didn't do anything.

554
01:00:52,482 --> 01:00:54,735
Call me Katherine.

555
01:00:54,901 --> 01:00:58,075
Katherine. I'm glad you're feeling better.

556
01:00:58,238 --> 01:01:02,209
- You have places to go, people to save?
- Yes.

557
01:01:05,871 --> 01:01:07,999
Would you like to get
a cup of coffee sometime?

558
01:01:08,165 --> 01:01:10,714
- I know that's forward. Or a drink?
- Good night.

559
01:01:10,876 --> 01:01:12,549
Good night.

560
01:01:22,971 --> 01:01:24,814
[SPEAKING GERMAN]

561
01:01:31,396 --> 01:01:33,023
It's like this on every channel.

562
01:01:33,190 --> 01:01:36,069
<i>MAN 1 [ON TV]: He was in Manila
at 10:55 p.m. and then spotted...</i>

563
01:01:36,234 --> 01:01:39,989
- Hey, Kent, chief wants to see you.
- Oh, thanks.

564
01:01:40,155 --> 01:01:44,126
WOMAN <i>1: But as this security footage
from a simple deli robbery proves...</i>

565
01:01:44,284 --> 01:01:47,413
<i>there's really no feat too big
or too small for the Man of Steel.</i>

566
01:01:47,579 --> 01:01:50,833
<i>Reports are flooding in from Metropolis,
Houston, Gotham and as far...</i>

567
01:01:50,999 --> 01:01:53,752
MAN <i>2: Satellites have proven
most ineffective at tracking him.</i>

568
01:01:53,919 --> 01:01:57,469
<i>He might literally be moving
near the speed of light.</i>

569
01:01:57,631 --> 01:02:00,225
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

570
01:02:10,685 --> 01:02:13,564
WOMAN 2: <i>Our map is illuminated...
- Kent!</i>

571
01:02:13,730 --> 01:02:16,779
<i>The chief is waiting.</i>
On <i>every continent, giving citizens...</i>

572
01:02:17,651 --> 01:02:18,868
LOIS: Eh.

573
01:02:19,027 --> 01:02:20,495
PERRY: Eh? Eh?

574
01:02:20,654 --> 01:02:24,375
These are iconic, and they were taken
by a 12-year-old with a camera phone.

575
01:02:24,532 --> 01:02:26,910
- What do you got, Olsen?
- I got those.

576
01:02:27,077 --> 01:02:28,545
[JIMMY CLEARS THROAT]

577
01:02:29,955 --> 01:02:31,555
- Look, in the sky, chief.
- It's a bird.

578
01:02:31,665 --> 01:02:33,025
- It's a plane.
- No, look, it's...

579
01:02:33,083 --> 01:02:34,585
[DOOR CLICKS OPEN]

580
01:02:34,751 --> 01:02:38,051
- You wanted to see me?
- Yeah, Kent, come on in. Sit down.

581
01:02:38,213 --> 01:02:41,217
I wanna talk a little strategy. Okay.

582
01:02:41,716 --> 01:02:44,390
First off, Lois, I don't understand
what you're doing...

583
01:02:44,552 --> 01:02:47,852
sneaking around covering the blackout.
It wasn't just a blackout.

584
01:02:48,014 --> 01:02:50,016
Cell phones, pagers,
automobiles, airplane...

585
01:02:50,183 --> 01:02:52,652
Every other paper in town
has got a female reporter...

586
01:02:52,811 --> 01:02:56,236
a good-looking female reporter,
stashed on the roof covering Superman.

587
01:02:56,398 --> 01:02:59,447
- And you two are the ones with history.
- Chief, I've done Superman.

588
01:02:59,609 --> 01:03:01,361
[JIMMY SNICKERS]

589
01:03:01,736 --> 01:03:03,784
Covered him. You know what I mean.

590
01:03:03,947 --> 01:03:06,120
Yeah, that makes you an expert.
Do him again.

591
01:03:06,283 --> 01:03:09,082
- There are a dozen other stories out there.
- Yeah? Name one.

592
01:03:09,244 --> 01:03:11,838
Well, there was a museum robbery
last night.

593
01:03:12,038 --> 01:03:15,793
Hm? Even Superman missed that one.
He was too busy saving this hooker.

594
01:03:15,959 --> 01:03:18,633
JIMMY: Why don't you guys
track down Lex Luthor?

595
01:03:19,337 --> 01:03:21,590
Well, no one's seen him
since his fifth appeal.

596
01:03:21,756 --> 01:03:23,929
He's got more bad history
with Superman than anyone.

597
01:03:24,092 --> 01:03:25,594
Maybe he's got something to say.

598
01:03:25,760 --> 01:03:29,515
- Luthor's yesterday's news.
- No, I like that idea.

599
01:03:30,473 --> 01:03:35,024
Perry, Lex Luthor is a career criminal
who nearly killed him, for God's sakes.

600
01:03:35,186 --> 01:03:37,439
Jimmy, how did Lex Luthor
get out of prison?

601
01:03:37,605 --> 01:03:41,610
Well, the appeals court called Superman
as a witness and he wasn't around.

602
01:03:42,319 --> 01:03:44,447
How much do you think
that pisses off Superman?

603
01:03:44,612 --> 01:03:46,239
LOIS: Give him to someone else.
- A lot.

604
01:03:46,406 --> 01:03:48,329
- A lot.
- Polly. Give him to Polly.

605
01:03:53,455 --> 01:03:55,002
Lois, Superman.

606
01:03:55,165 --> 01:03:57,384
- What about the blackout?
- Kent, blackout.

607
01:03:58,209 --> 01:03:59,426
[MOUTHS]

608
01:03:59,961 --> 01:04:02,305
Great. Thanks, chief.

609
01:04:05,425 --> 01:04:10,272
Lois, I'm sorry. I'd hate if this
damaged our relationship.

610
01:04:11,598 --> 01:04:12,724
Relationship?

611
01:04:13,475 --> 01:04:14,897
Yeah. JASON: Hi, Mommy.

612
01:04:15,060 --> 01:04:16,937
Hi, you. RICHARD: Hey, guys.

613
01:04:17,103 --> 01:04:20,903
He got an A in science, but a D in gym,
so we're doing something right.

614
01:04:21,066 --> 01:04:23,068
LOIS: Yeah, at least one of us is.
- What?

615
01:04:23,234 --> 01:04:26,078
It's Perry. He just shoved Superman
back into my life.

616
01:04:26,237 --> 01:04:29,207
Well, honey, I'm sure you can
find a way to interview Superman...

617
01:04:29,366 --> 01:04:31,368
without bringing him
back into your life.

618
01:04:31,534 --> 01:04:35,835
<i>There's really no way around it, folks.
Superman is back in all of our lives.</i>

619
01:04:36,039 --> 01:04:37,131
[PEOPLE CHEERING ON TV]

620
01:04:37,290 --> 01:04:39,088
<i>We're coming to you from Sydney...</i>

621
01:04:39,250 --> 01:04:42,003
<i>where people have gathered
on these rooftops to scour the sky...</i>

622
01:04:42,170 --> 01:04:43,217
[JASON WHEEZING]

623
01:04:43,380 --> 01:04:46,429
Okay, how about this?
We'll stay late. We'll get dinner.

624
01:04:46,591 --> 01:04:50,221
I'll help with Superman, and you and
Clark can work on the blackout together.

625
01:04:50,387 --> 01:04:53,357
- Is that all right with you, Clark?
- Swell.

626
01:04:56,142 --> 01:04:59,487
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYS
ON STEREO]

627
01:05:17,247 --> 01:05:21,297
I was gonna pretend
the brakes were out.

628
01:05:21,459 --> 01:05:24,588
Pretend. Like we talked about.

629
01:05:24,754 --> 01:05:27,553
You didn't actually have to cut them!

630
01:05:27,715 --> 01:05:29,012
Of course I did.

631
01:05:29,175 --> 01:05:33,396
A man can always tell when a woman
is pretending, especially Superman.

632
01:05:33,555 --> 01:05:35,728
Mm, mm, mm.

633
01:05:38,893 --> 01:05:41,271
So did you get your rock?

634
01:05:42,647 --> 01:05:44,570
I did.

635
01:05:45,942 --> 01:05:48,286
MAN [ON RADIO]: U. S. Coast
Guard issuing a <i>small-craft...</i>

636
01:05:48,445 --> 01:05:50,163
<i>advisory for the Metropolis ocean area.</i>

637
01:05:50,321 --> 01:05:51,994
<i>High-wind advisory is in effect...</i>

638
01:05:52,157 --> 01:05:55,036
<i>ocean currents and tides
becoming increasingly dangerous.</i>

639
01:05:55,201 --> 01:05:58,421
<i>All warnings lasting
until later this evening.</i>

640
01:05:58,580 --> 01:05:59,832
<i>Security, security.</i>

641
01:05:59,998 --> 01:06:05,471
<i>This is U.S. Coast Guard issuing
a small-craft advisory for northeast seas.</i>

642
01:06:05,628 --> 01:06:10,099
<i>Winds reaching 50 miles per hour,
high tides in the morning.</i>

643
01:06:10,258 --> 01:06:12,101
<i>Waves reaching 20 to 30 feet.</i>

644
01:06:12,260 --> 01:06:16,265
<i>This warning is in effect for
all small crafts for the next four hours.</i>

645
01:06:26,816 --> 01:06:28,489
[BUZZING]

646
01:06:40,371 --> 01:06:41,998
LOIS:
Weird. If these times are right...

647
01:06:42,165 --> 01:06:45,260
the blackout spread
from a specific origin point.

648
01:06:45,418 --> 01:06:46,795
RICHARD: Where?

649
01:06:46,961 --> 01:06:48,759
I'm not sure yet.

650
01:06:49,464 --> 01:06:53,139
With the super-hearing, does he hear each
sound by itself or everything at once?

651
01:06:53,510 --> 01:06:54,762
LOIS: Both.

652
01:06:54,928 --> 01:06:57,147
<i>He's certainly taller than I thought.
LOIS ". 6'4".</i>

653
01:06:57,305 --> 01:07:01,060
I love that he can see through anything.
I'd have fun with that.

654
01:07:01,434 --> 01:07:03,152
<i>LOIS: Anything but lead.</i>

655
01:07:03,311 --> 01:07:05,109
[ROARING]

656
01:07:06,397 --> 01:07:07,649
- I bet he's...
- 225 pounds...

657
01:07:07,815 --> 01:07:09,488
faster than a speeding bullet...

658
01:07:09,651 --> 01:07:13,121
draws his power from the sun,
invulnerable to anything but kryptonite...

659
01:07:13,279 --> 01:07:15,327
- and he never lies.
- I'm?

660
01:07:15,490 --> 01:07:17,834
Radioactive pieces of his home world.

661
01:07:17,992 --> 01:07:20,211
It's deadly. To him.

662
01:07:24,791 --> 01:07:28,170
Lois, how tall would you say Clark is?

663
01:07:29,712 --> 01:07:31,714
<i>LOIS: About 6'3 ", 6'4".</i>

664
01:07:31,881 --> 01:07:34,680
<i>RICHARD: About 200, 215 pounds?</i>

665
01:07:44,644 --> 01:07:48,649
Jimmy, Jason, let's go get these intrepid
reporters something to keep them going.

666
01:07:48,815 --> 01:07:50,692
JASON: Burritos!
RICHARD: Come here, canhead.

667
01:07:52,193 --> 01:07:56,164
We're going this way. Do they have
anything other than burritos?

668
01:07:57,031 --> 01:07:59,375
JIMMY:
I think they have fries and burgers.

669
01:07:59,534 --> 01:08:02,037
So have you found a place to live yet?

670
01:08:02,203 --> 01:08:03,796
Uh, no. I'm still looking.

671
01:08:04,539 --> 01:08:07,042
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

672
01:08:07,208 --> 01:08:10,337
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

673
01:08:10,503 --> 01:08:12,050
[LOIS SIGHS]

674
01:08:24,475 --> 01:08:26,193
Thanks.

675
01:08:33,985 --> 01:08:36,738
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

676
01:09:30,249 --> 01:09:33,002
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

677
01:09:36,297 --> 01:09:38,800
- Sorry. Didn't mean to startle you.
- No, I'm fine. Really.

678
01:09:40,927 --> 01:09:44,056
I just wasn't expecting you.

679
01:09:44,722 --> 01:09:46,315
With all the press on the plane...

680
01:09:46,474 --> 01:09:48,897
I wasn't sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

681
01:09:49,060 --> 01:09:52,234
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

682
01:09:54,440 --> 01:09:56,909
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

683
01:09:57,276 --> 01:10:00,826
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

684
01:10:02,490 --> 01:10:05,835
So you're here for an interview?

685
01:10:07,078 --> 01:10:08,125
Okay, then.

686
01:10:11,999 --> 01:10:14,001
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

687
01:10:20,133 --> 01:10:22,852
Let's start with the big question.

688
01:10:23,010 --> 01:10:25,513
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

689
01:10:25,680 --> 01:10:28,058
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

690
01:10:28,224 --> 01:10:29,692
It was.

691
01:10:29,851 --> 01:10:32,229
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

692
01:10:33,688 --> 01:10:36,066
I had to see for myself.

693
01:10:39,694 --> 01:10:43,540
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

694
01:10:46,743 --> 01:10:48,211
Not everyone.

695
01:10:49,370 --> 01:10:51,793
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

696
01:10:51,956 --> 01:10:54,926
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

697
01:10:56,586 --> 01:10:58,634
How could you leave us like that?

698
01:11:00,131 --> 01:11:02,554
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

699
01:11:03,050 --> 01:11:04,552
That's why I wrote it.

700
01:11:04,719 --> 01:11:07,518
The world doesn't need a savior.

701
01:11:07,930 --> 01:11:09,853
And neither do I.

702
01:11:24,989 --> 01:11:26,081
Lois.

703
01:11:27,784 --> 01:11:30,253
Will you come with me?

704
01:11:31,996 --> 01:11:33,589
Why?

705
01:11:33,956 --> 01:11:36,084
There's something I wanna show you.

706
01:11:42,340 --> 01:11:44,138
Please.

707
01:11:55,144 --> 01:11:57,317
I can't be gone long.

708
01:11:57,480 --> 01:11:59,403
You won't be.

709
01:12:11,786 --> 01:12:14,539
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

710
01:12:14,705 --> 01:12:17,003
is because it was
too unbearable for you.

711
01:12:17,166 --> 01:12:19,794
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

712
01:12:20,378 --> 01:12:23,552
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

713
01:12:24,632 --> 01:12:26,760
Maybe Clark's right.

714
01:12:30,137 --> 01:12:32,265
You know, my...

715
01:12:32,431 --> 01:12:37,483
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

716
01:12:38,646 --> 01:12:40,648
Not like this.

717
01:12:42,817 --> 01:12:44,569
[GASPS]

718
01:12:55,496 --> 01:12:57,919
I forgot how warm you were.

719
01:13:28,529 --> 01:13:30,031
SUPERMAN: Listen.

720
01:13:30,907 --> 01:13:32,830
What do you hear?

721
01:13:33,534 --> 01:13:34,786
Nothing.

722
01:13:38,706 --> 01:13:40,458
I hear everything.

723
01:13:43,920 --> 01:13:46,548
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

724
01:13:47,882 --> 01:13:51,227
but every day
I hear people crying for one.

725
01:14:04,065 --> 01:14:06,739
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

726
01:14:10,613 --> 01:14:12,661
I'll take you back now.

727
01:16:25,790 --> 01:16:27,417
Richard's a good man.

728
01:16:30,836 --> 01:16:33,055
And you've been gone a long time.

729
01:16:35,716 --> 01:16:37,309
I know.

730
01:16:42,056 --> 01:16:43,399
I...

731
01:16:45,142 --> 01:16:46,815
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

732
01:16:48,604 --> 01:16:50,606
So will I see you around?

733
01:16:51,607 --> 01:16:53,609
I'm always around.

734
01:16:54,902 --> 01:16:56,620
Good night, Lois.

735
01:17:15,589 --> 01:17:19,469
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

736
01:17:23,264 --> 01:17:24,857
You all right?

737
01:17:25,015 --> 01:17:26,517
LOIS: Mm-hm.

738
01:17:26,684 --> 01:17:28,106
Where have you been?

739
01:17:30,938 --> 01:17:32,281
Uh...

740
01:17:32,481 --> 01:17:38,113
I was up on the roof, getting some air.

741
01:17:38,779 --> 01:17:40,747
Tell the truth now.

742
01:17:47,288 --> 01:17:48,460
Were you smoking?

743
01:17:51,083 --> 01:17:52,835
No.

744
01:18:01,635 --> 01:18:02,852
Is this real?

745
01:18:03,888 --> 01:18:05,765
- Where'd you find him?
- He found me.

746
01:18:05,931 --> 01:18:08,730
Oh, this is great. I can't wait to read it.

747
01:18:08,893 --> 01:18:11,316
So, Mr. White, about the blackout...

748
01:18:11,478 --> 01:18:13,981
Lois, this is the biggest night
of your life.

749
01:18:14,148 --> 01:18:16,321
Have you picked out a dress?
Something snazzy?

750
01:18:17,318 --> 01:18:20,037
It just feels a little weird
winning for that article.

751
01:18:20,196 --> 01:18:23,245
- It just doesn't seem right.
- What doesn't seem right?

752
01:18:23,407 --> 01:18:25,125
Winning an award for an article called:

753
01:18:25,284 --> 01:18:27,002
"Why the World
Doesn't Need Superman."

754
01:18:27,161 --> 01:18:29,630
When, according
to this newspaper, they do.

755
01:18:29,788 --> 01:18:32,712
Lois, Pulitzer Prizes
are like Academy Awards.

756
01:18:32,875 --> 01:18:36,004
Nobody remembers what you got one for.
It's just that you got one.

757
01:18:36,170 --> 01:18:39,299
- But...
- This is your night. You enjoy it.

758
01:18:39,465 --> 01:18:42,014
I'm sure Kent's on the blackout.

759
01:19:42,569 --> 01:19:44,788
LOIS:
Department of Water and Power, please.

760
01:19:45,489 --> 01:19:46,786
7782, great.

761
01:19:48,242 --> 01:19:49,744
Metropolis Public Works.

762
01:19:49,910 --> 01:19:52,413
Hi, Stephen, Lois Lane
from the <i>Daily</i> Planet. Blackout?

763
01:19:52,579 --> 01:19:55,298
I just need a little info
on a few outstanding power grids.

764
01:19:55,457 --> 01:19:57,084
<i>LOIS:
Yeah, I do have it here, actually.</i>

765
01:19:57,251 --> 01:20:01,256
<i>So the uptown grid went dark at 12:36
and midtown 10 seconds before.</i>

766
01:20:01,422 --> 01:20:02,924
Which grid was hit first?

767
01:20:03,090 --> 01:20:04,450
<i>"WOMAN".
It just reads Vanderworth.</i>

768
01:20:04,591 --> 01:20:06,969
<i>- Across the river?
- 6 Springwood Drive.</i>

769
01:20:07,136 --> 01:20:09,389
6 Springwood Drive.
A residence or a business?

770
01:20:09,555 --> 01:20:11,307
<i>- Residence.
- Sure? Nothing before that?</i>

771
01:20:11,473 --> 01:20:13,817
- That's all <i>it</i> shows.
- Thank you very much.

772
01:20:15,644 --> 01:20:16,941
Oh, Jason.

773
01:20:22,109 --> 01:20:23,361
[TIRES SCREECH]

774
01:20:23,736 --> 01:20:26,956
WOMAN: There's your mom, Jason.
JASON: You're late, Mommy.

775
01:20:35,164 --> 01:20:38,008
Where are we? Ls this the Pulitzer?

776
01:20:38,167 --> 01:20:41,171
Nope. I've just gotta ask these people
a few questions and then we can go.

777
01:20:41,337 --> 01:20:43,339
[PHONE RINGING]

778
01:20:56,769 --> 01:20:59,147
JASON: Can I stay in the car?

779
01:20:59,688 --> 01:21:01,281
LOIS: No, honey.

780
01:21:01,607 --> 01:21:05,111
[OPERA MUSIC BLASTS FROM STEREO]

781
01:21:07,946 --> 01:21:12,326
JASON: Are we trespassing?
- No. Yes. Shh.

782
01:21:27,049 --> 01:21:28,892
Hello?

783
01:21:48,320 --> 01:21:50,448
[PHONE RINGING]

784
01:22:00,374 --> 01:22:01,921
Hello?

785
01:22:13,011 --> 01:22:15,605
JASON: I like the curly one.

786
01:22:22,896 --> 01:22:25,740
Let's go. This was a bad idea.

787
01:22:26,316 --> 01:22:27,909
[MOTOR STARTS]

788
01:22:41,457 --> 01:22:43,255
Lex Luthor.

789
01:22:45,252 --> 01:22:47,380
Lois Lane?

790
01:22:53,177 --> 01:22:54,520
You're bald.

791
01:23:14,615 --> 01:23:15,992
And what is your name?

792
01:23:16,158 --> 01:23:18,627
I'm not supposed to talk to strangers.

793
01:23:19,119 --> 01:23:21,087
- Cute kid, and smart.
LOIS: Thanks.

794
01:23:21,246 --> 01:23:24,466
We're not really strangers, are we?
This is kind of a little reunion.

795
01:23:24,625 --> 01:23:26,673
Heck, I'm a fan.

796
01:23:26,835 --> 01:23:28,337
I love your writing...

797
01:23:29,171 --> 01:23:31,014
and your dress.
LOIS: I love your boat.

798
01:23:31,173 --> 01:23:33,801
How'd you get it?
Swindle some widow out of her money?

799
01:23:35,135 --> 01:23:37,388
That's funny. Didn't you win
the Pulitzer Prize...

800
01:23:37,554 --> 01:23:41,149
for my favorite article of all time,
"Why the World Doesn't Need Superman"?

801
01:23:41,308 --> 01:23:45,233
Didn't you have a few more years to go
on that double life sentence?

802
01:23:45,395 --> 01:23:47,648
Yes, well, we can thank
the Man of Steel for that.

803
01:23:47,814 --> 01:23:51,114
I mean, he's really good at swooping in
and catching the bad guys...

804
01:23:51,276 --> 01:23:54,826
but he's not so hot at the little
things, like Miranda rights...

805
01:23:54,988 --> 01:23:59,710
due process, making your court date.

806
01:23:59,868 --> 01:24:02,337
Did you have anything to do
with the blackout?

807
01:24:05,332 --> 01:24:07,551
Are you fishing for an interview,
Miss Lane?

808
01:24:07,709 --> 01:24:09,882
It's been a while
since you've been a headline.

809
01:24:10,045 --> 01:24:12,218
Maybe it's time
people knew your name again.

810
01:24:12,881 --> 01:24:16,852
How about we turn this boat around,
call a cab for my son...

811
01:24:17,386 --> 01:24:20,014
and then you can do
whatever you want with me.

812
01:24:20,722 --> 01:24:23,271
No, I don't think we'll be
turning around, Miss Lane...

813
01:24:23,433 --> 01:24:26,061
which means that
we do have some time to kill.

814
01:24:28,230 --> 01:24:30,107
How about that interview?

815
01:24:31,024 --> 01:24:34,369
Yeah, just call me if you hear anything.
Okay. Thank you.

816
01:24:34,945 --> 01:24:36,242
So, what did the school say?

817
01:24:36,405 --> 01:24:37,907
She picked him up at 3:15.

818
01:24:42,160 --> 01:24:45,460
- Hi, I heard about Lois.
- Yes, come in, Clark, come in.

819
01:24:45,622 --> 01:24:48,125
- Is there anything I can do?
- Yeah, you're a reporter.

820
01:24:48,292 --> 01:24:51,045
- Help Richard track her down.
- I'll check her computer.

821
01:24:51,211 --> 01:24:52,463
Excuse me, Clark.

822
01:25:06,184 --> 01:25:09,279
What do you know about crystals?

823
01:25:09,438 --> 01:25:11,156
They make great chandeliers.

824
01:25:11,732 --> 01:25:16,738
This crystal may seem unremarkable,
but so is the seed of a redwood tree.

825
01:25:16,903 --> 01:25:20,328
It's how our mutual friend in tights
made his Arctic getaway spot.

826
01:25:20,490 --> 01:25:22,367
Cute. It's a little small for my taste.

827
01:25:22,534 --> 01:25:24,081
You're building an island?

828
01:25:25,287 --> 01:25:28,632
You're not seeing
the big picture here, Miss Lane.

829
01:25:28,790 --> 01:25:31,088
Let me enlarge it for you.

830
01:25:33,670 --> 01:25:37,095
Not just an island,
an entirely new continent.

831
01:25:37,257 --> 01:25:40,511
An extinct world, reborn on our own.

832
01:25:40,677 --> 01:25:42,099
Why?

833
01:25:45,098 --> 01:25:47,021
Land, Miss Lane.

834
01:25:47,184 --> 01:25:49,937
I mean... Kitty, what did my father
used to say to me?

835
01:25:50,103 --> 01:25:51,525
"You're losing your hair"?

836
01:25:52,522 --> 01:25:54,445
- Before that.
- "Get out"?

837
01:25:55,984 --> 01:25:58,282
He said, "You can print money..."

838
01:25:58,445 --> 01:26:01,073
manufacture diamonds,
and people are a dime a dozen...

839
01:26:01,239 --> 01:26:04,334
"but they'll always need land."

840
01:26:04,493 --> 01:26:07,337
It's the one thing
they're not making any more of.

841
01:26:07,871 --> 01:26:09,965
But the United States...

842
01:26:10,123 --> 01:26:11,750
Whoop.

843
01:26:11,958 --> 01:26:15,462
Will be underwater.

844
01:26:15,879 --> 01:26:17,472
It's simple physics, Miss Lane.

845
01:26:17,631 --> 01:26:20,430
Two objects cannot occupy
the same space at the same time.

846
01:26:20,592 --> 01:26:23,141
And the rest of the world
will just let you keep it?

847
01:26:23,303 --> 01:26:25,522
- They'll...
- They'll...

848
01:26:26,014 --> 01:26:27,482
what?

849
01:26:27,641 --> 01:26:30,520
I'll have advanced alien technology...

850
01:26:30,686 --> 01:26:33,735
thousands of years beyond
what anyone could throw at me.

851
01:26:33,897 --> 01:26:35,945
Bring it on!

852
01:26:36,942 --> 01:26:38,865
And eventually...

853
01:26:39,027 --> 01:26:41,371
the rest of the world
will be begging me...

854
01:26:41,530 --> 01:26:44,158
for a piece of high-tech
beachfront property.

855
01:26:44,324 --> 01:26:46,668
In fact, they'll pay
through the nose for it.

856
01:26:47,077 --> 01:26:48,829
But millions of people will die.

857
01:26:48,995 --> 01:26:51,623
Billions! Once again,
the press underestimates me.

858
01:26:51,790 --> 01:26:54,168
This is front-page news.

859
01:26:54,835 --> 01:26:56,837
Come on, let me hear you say it
just once.

860
01:26:57,003 --> 01:27:01,509
- You're insane.
- No! Not that. No, the other thing.

861
01:27:01,675 --> 01:27:05,350
It's dangling off the tip of your tongue.
Let me hear it just once, please?

862
01:27:05,512 --> 01:27:08,516
- Superman will never...
- Wrong!

863
01:27:21,737 --> 01:27:23,364
What is that?

864
01:27:24,573 --> 01:27:27,372
I think you know exactly what this is.

865
01:27:33,373 --> 01:27:36,252
Mind over muscle, Miss Lane.

866
01:27:37,377 --> 01:27:39,175
Mind...

867
01:27:46,720 --> 01:27:48,722
Who is that boy's father?

868
01:27:50,223 --> 01:27:52,100
Richard.

869
01:27:52,559 --> 01:27:56,063
THUG: <i>Mr. Luthor, we're approaching
the coordinates.</i>

870
01:27:56,646 --> 01:27:58,239
Are you sure?

871
01:27:58,398 --> 01:28:03,746
<i>Yes, sir. Latitude 40 degrees north,
longitude 73 degrees west.</i>

872
01:28:25,258 --> 01:28:27,431
Don't let them leave this room.

873
01:28:27,761 --> 01:28:30,355
Kitty, come with me.
You're not gonna want to miss this.

874
01:29:38,874 --> 01:29:40,296
[BUZZING]

875
01:29:43,420 --> 01:29:44,797
RICHARD: Damn it. CLARK: What?

876
01:29:44,963 --> 01:29:46,180
She has a password.

877
01:29:48,174 --> 01:29:49,767
"Jason."

878
01:29:51,845 --> 01:29:53,563
"Richard."

879
01:29:55,473 --> 01:29:57,066
Try "Superman."

880
01:30:02,188 --> 01:30:04,611
"Superman." Great.

881
01:30:12,949 --> 01:30:15,043
Don't touch that, honey.

882
01:30:19,289 --> 01:30:21,758
Why don't you go play the piano.

883
01:30:41,186 --> 01:30:44,030
[PLAYS "CHOPSTICKS"]

884
01:31:31,486 --> 01:31:33,739
[MUTTERING]

885
01:32:18,992 --> 01:32:21,495
Come OH, come on, come on.

886
01:33:09,751 --> 01:33:11,970
[BOOMS]

887
01:34:05,265 --> 01:34:07,393
[THUNDER CRASHING]

888
01:34:08,560 --> 01:34:11,609
Lex, this isn't like the train set.

889
01:34:13,523 --> 01:34:15,275
I know.

890
01:34:21,322 --> 01:34:23,120
Come on, come on.

891
01:34:23,741 --> 01:34:24,958
Come on.

892
01:34:30,707 --> 01:34:32,459
[THUG YELLS]

893
01:34:33,877 --> 01:34:34,969
[WHEEZING]

894
01:34:42,635 --> 01:34:44,512
[GROANING]

895
01:35:52,872 --> 01:35:54,749
- Honey, are you okay?
- Yeah.

896
01:35:54,916 --> 01:35:56,918
- Are you hurt?
- I'm fine.

897
01:35:58,127 --> 01:36:00,880
Open this door! Open it!

898
01:36:16,229 --> 01:36:18,607
Could you help Mommy open the door?

899
01:36:21,484 --> 01:36:23,236
I'm sorry.

900
01:36:26,322 --> 01:36:28,416
It's gonna be okay.

901
01:36:28,574 --> 01:36:30,918
Okay? It's gonna be okay.

902
01:36:50,596 --> 01:36:54,066
We had a little problem downstairs.

903
01:36:54,600 --> 01:36:56,773
Brutus is dead.

904
01:36:57,437 --> 01:37:00,691
He got hit with the piano.

905
01:37:05,278 --> 01:37:07,155
Where's the boy?

906
01:37:07,322 --> 01:37:11,452
With the mother,
locked up in the pantry.

907
01:37:13,619 --> 01:37:15,792
Oh, it's time for us to go.

908
01:37:21,794 --> 01:37:24,297
My camera's not working.

909
01:37:25,089 --> 01:37:27,217
And my phone's not working.

910
01:37:32,263 --> 01:37:35,016
- Okay, I'm good.
- That was weird.

911
01:37:49,989 --> 01:37:52,333
Hey, guys.
This just came through the fax.

912
01:37:52,492 --> 01:37:54,790
It's Lois' handwriting,
I'd recognize it anywhere.

913
01:37:54,952 --> 01:37:56,795
I just... No idea
what the numbers mean.

914
01:37:56,954 --> 01:37:58,706
- They're coordinates.
- Coordinates.

915
01:38:00,833 --> 01:38:02,050
That's just off the coast.

916
01:38:02,210 --> 01:38:05,339
Jimmy, tell Perry I'm taking the seaplane.
Keep trying her cell.

917
01:38:07,840 --> 01:38:09,137
[SIGHS]

918
01:39:09,735 --> 01:39:12,579
[THUNDER CRASHING]

919
01:39:22,457 --> 01:39:24,175
Agh!

920
01:39:39,765 --> 01:39:41,813
[DOG BARKING]

921
01:39:58,701 --> 01:40:00,795
[RUMBLING]

922
01:40:09,504 --> 01:40:10,972
What are these, lottery numbers?

923
01:40:11,506 --> 01:40:13,508
I think they're coordinates, chief.

924
01:40:18,137 --> 01:40:19,855
[RUMBLING]

925
01:40:52,213 --> 01:40:53,385
Chief...

926
01:41:11,440 --> 01:41:12,692
Ah!

927
01:41:19,115 --> 01:41:20,162
[HONKING]

928
01:41:20,324 --> 01:41:22,577
Come on! Move it!

929
01:41:23,703 --> 01:41:25,250
[CREAKING]

930
01:41:39,176 --> 01:41:41,270
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

931
01:43:15,898 --> 01:43:17,650
[CREAKING]

932
01:43:26,367 --> 01:43:28,369
[DISTANT CREAKING]

933
01:43:28,577 --> 01:43:30,329
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

934
01:43:46,303 --> 01:43:47,976
Chief!

935
01:43:59,150 --> 01:44:01,573
Great Caesar's ghost.

936
01:44:04,530 --> 01:44:07,204
[CHEERING]

937
01:46:08,529 --> 01:46:10,657
- Daddy.
- Oh, my God.

938
01:46:24,253 --> 01:46:25,675
How did you get here?

939
01:46:25,838 --> 01:46:27,511
I flew.

940
01:46:31,176 --> 01:46:33,019
RICHARD: Look out!

941
01:46:45,858 --> 01:46:47,576
Mom!

942
01:46:47,735 --> 01:46:49,863
Mom! Mom!

943
01:46:50,029 --> 01:46:51,406
LOIS: Jason, come here! Jason!

944
01:46:54,283 --> 01:46:56,206
Come here! Watch your head!
Come here!

945
01:47:02,791 --> 01:47:04,714
[SCREAMING]

946
01:47:19,224 --> 01:47:20,771
[SHIP CREAKING AND GROANING]

947
01:47:35,240 --> 01:47:36,708
[SCREAMING]

948
01:47:56,720 --> 01:47:58,518
Mommy! Mom!

949
01:48:00,432 --> 01:48:01,684
LOIS: Jason!

950
01:48:05,145 --> 01:48:06,647
Jason, hold on!

951
01:48:09,775 --> 01:48:12,449
- Have you got him?
- I got him! Go!

952
01:48:14,863 --> 01:48:16,456
Hold on! Hold on!

953
01:48:31,171 --> 01:48:32,514
- Mommy!
- Give him to me!

954
01:48:32,673 --> 01:48:34,266
Mommy!

955
01:48:34,883 --> 01:48:36,806
- Mommy! Mommy!
- Come on, Jason! Come on!

956
01:48:40,639 --> 01:48:43,483
- RICHARD: Lois! Lois!
- Mommy!

957
01:48:57,740 --> 01:48:59,117
[GRUNTING AND GASPING]

958
01:49:47,956 --> 01:49:50,050
RICHARD: Jason, get on my back.

959
01:50:20,072 --> 01:50:21,745
Give me your hand.

960
01:50:29,164 --> 01:50:31,462
- Have you got them?
- Yeah.

961
01:50:50,561 --> 01:50:52,484
RICHARD: Get buckled in!

962
01:51:11,498 --> 01:51:13,375
She'll be fine.

963
01:51:16,128 --> 01:51:17,505
I can't take off in this.

964
01:51:17,671 --> 01:51:21,642
<i>- I'll</i> point you in the right direction.
- Thank you.

965
01:51:55,334 --> 01:51:57,962
